COVID Analysis: Philippines vs Japan

K. Chu

9/25/2021

Im from the Philippines, and I got curious how the situation looks like. However, I have moved to Japan for work, and Im also curious what the situation looks like here. Am I safer here in Japan, or should I go back home to the Philippines?

# rename the columns with slashes
global_cases <- global_cases %>% 
  rename(Country_Region=`Country/Region`,
         Province_State=`Province/State`) 

global_deaths <- global_deaths %>% 
  rename(Country_Region=`Country/Region`,
         Province_State=`Province/State`) 

global_recoveries <- global_recoveries %>% 
  rename(Country_Region=`Country/Region`,
         Province_State=`Province/State`)

I am getting my data from the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins University. They have a GitHub repository for global cases, deaths, and recoveries, so I will be using this repository.

The three files here contain a lot of information, but they show a tally of cases or deaths or recoveries per country per day, with each day being a new column. We have a very wide table. Since I want to more easily see the number of cases, deaths, and recoveries, I will have to transform the data.

However, for recoveries, it appears that we dont have recorded data past August 4, 2021, as we get 0s from August 5, 2021 onward. I will also have to address this in my transformation.

recoveries_last_available_date <- "2021-08-04"
# get philippine cases
ph_cases <- global_cases %>% 
  filter(Country_Region == "Philippines") %>%
  pivot_longer(cols= -c(Province_State,
                        Country_Region,
                        Lat,
                        Long),
               names_to="date",
               values_to="cases") %>%
  select(-c(Lat, Long))

Here, I filtered out the data for the Philippines. I also transformed the tables using pivot_longer so that I can more easily visualize the data. I joined the two tables together so that I can pair the number of cases with the number of deaths. Im also more interested in seeing things after the Philippines started having cases, so I only retained the rows that had at least one case.

As of this writing, the latest entry was for September 23, 2021, with the number of total cases over time being 2,434,753 and the number of total deaths being 37,405. The number of recoveries, as of August 4, 2021, is 1,528,422.

It didnt look so good for the Philippines at first, but the numbers went back down. The case fatality rate for both countries appears to have settled to almost close to 0. Lets take a closer look at things in 2021.

According to this graph, the case fatality rates went way down, below 0.02.

The lower bound for the Philippines appears to be 0.015 while it is 0.010 for Japan.

This is great since this means that COVID is not particularly fatal. It appears that for every 100 cases, I can expect around 1 or 2 deaths in the Philippines while I can expect close to 1 death in Japan.

I would like to create a model to see how things would play out in the future. I think its more accurate to use only this years data with regards to case fatality rate since the outbreak was such a sudden shock to the world last year. I think now that the world has had a chance to stabilize somewhat, this years numbers should be more relevant.

mod_ph <- lm(deaths_to_cases ~ date, data=ph_data_2021)
summary(mod_ph)
##

## lm(formula = deaths_to_cases ~ date, data = ph_data_2021)

## 
## Coefficients:

## (Intercept)  3.328e-01  1.585e-02   21.00   <2e-16 ***
## date        -1.677e-05  8.446e-07  -19.86   <2e-16 ***

## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.001058 on 264 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.599,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.5975 
## F-statistic: 394.4 on 1 and 264 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
ph_w_pred <- ph_data_2021 %>% mutate(pred = predict(mod_ph))

ph_w_pred %>% ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=date, y=deaths_to_cases), color="blue") + 
  geom_point(aes(x=date, y=pred), color="red") +
  theme(legend.position="bottom",
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90)) +
  labs(title="Philippine 2021 Case Fatality Rate: Actual vs Model",
       y="Case Fatality Rate",
       x="Date")

mod_jp <- lm(deaths_to_cases ~ date, data=jp_data_2021)

jp_w_pred %>% ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=date, y=deaths_to_cases), color="blue") + 
  geom_point(aes(x=date, y=pred), color="red") +
  theme(legend.position="bottom",
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90)) +
  labs(title="Japan 2021 Case Fatality Rate: Actual vs Model",
       y="Case Fatality Rate",
       x="Date")

Both models predict a downward trend for both countries. This is great news, especially after taking into consideration that my model predicts that the ratio of deaths to cases is higher than was observed in September 2021.

Conclusion

It appears that there is a downward trend in the case fatality rates for both countries. The rates for both countries appear to continue going down, as predicted by my models.

It appears that Japan has a slightly lower case fatality rate as of September 2021. Perhaps it was a good thing for me to have come here, after all. I do miss seeing my family, however.

I could only look forward to the day that the numbers say zero. However, this may be impossible, and I have to temper my expectations so.

I have heard that age is a comorbidity when it came to COVID. Given that Japans population is aging, I would have expected that Japans case fatality rate would have been higher. However, I should also take into consideration that Japans healthcare system could be superior compared to the Philippiness.

Focusing solely on raw cases, deaths, and recoveries might not paint an accurate picture, so I opted to go for a metric like the case fatality rate. This would control for the different numbers of cases and deaths.
